05133nam a22007815i 9780823298426DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20212021nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232984267 a10.1515/97808232984262doi  a(DE-B1597)612815  a(OCoLC)1267760727  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPHI0270002bisacsh04a1942231 aNaas, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aClass Acts :bDerrida on the Public Stage /cMichael Naas. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (192 p.) :b1 b/w illustration  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPerspectives in Continental Philosophy00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations of Works Cited -- tIntroduction: The Program -- tPART I. Derrida in Montreal (A Play in Three Speech Acts) -- tArgument and Dramatis Personae -- tAct 1: The Context (1971) -- tAct 2: The Signature (1979) -- tAct 3: The Event (1997) -- tPART II. The Open Seminar -- tThe Counter- Program: Syllabus -- tClass 1: Agrégations The Chance of Life Death (1975–76) -- tClass 2: Education in Theory and Practice (1976–77) -- tClass 3: Grace and the Machine: Perjury and Pardon (1997–98) -- tConclusion: Actes de naissance -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tPerspectives in Continental Philosophy0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aClass Acts examines two often neglected aspects of Jacques Derrida’s work as a philosopher, his public presentations at lectures and conferences and his teaching, along with the question of the “speech act” that links them. What, Michael Naas asks, is one doing when one speaks in public in these ways?The book follows Derrida’s itinerary with regard to speech act theory across three public lectures, from 1971 to 1997, all given, for reasons the book seeks to explain, in Montreal. In these lectures, Derrida elaborated his critique of J. L. Austin and his own subsequent redefinition of speech act theory. The book then gives an overview of Derrida’s teaching career and his famous “seminar” presentations, along with his own explicit reflections on pedagogy and educational institutions beginning in the mid-1970s. Naas then shows through a reading of three recently published seminars—on life death, theory and practice, and forgiveness—just how Derrida the teacher interrogated and deployed speech act theory in his seminars. Whether in a conference hall or a classroom, Naas demonstrates, Derrida was always interested in the way spoken or written words might do more than simply communicate some meaning or intent but might give rise to something like an event. Class Acts bears witness to the possibility of such events in Derrida’s work as a pedagogue and a public intellectual.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aSpeech acts (Linguistics). 4aLiterary Studies. 4aPhilosophy & Theory. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Deconstruction.2bisacsh  aDeconstruction.  aJacques Derrida.  aPedagogy.  aPerformativity.  aSpeech Act Theory.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2021 Englishz978311075415508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2021z9783110753929oZDB-23-DPH08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073909140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823298426?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823298426423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823298426/original  a978-3-11-073909-1  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a9